    "# Risk Assessment for Heat wave"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "ee6eb462-41b7-4cfd-8ed5-1de60b32d3e1",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "To know more about how climate change can influence heat occurrence go to the climate-adapt web or use the hazard assessment toolbox from CLIMAAX:\n",
    "- Heat days for past [https://climate-adapt.eea.europa.eu/en/metadata/indicators/high-utci-days]\n",
    "- Heat wave days projections [https://climate-adapt.eea.europa.eu/en/metadata/indicators/apparent-temperature-heatwave-days]\n",
    "- Tropical nights [https://climate-adapt.eea.europa.eu/en/observatory/++aq++metadata/indicators/tropical-nights/]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "ec692076-55dc-4c21-8754-00ad76e6db01",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Risk assessment methodology"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "c0217eba-b7d5-46d2-ae6c-b46d364dca1f",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The risk assessment methodology is based on the combination of overheated areas and distribution of the vulnerable population, and areas with usually overcrowded places during the day. The identification of the overheated areas is based on the Land Surface Temperature product from the Landsat8 satellite imagery from the RSLAB webpage [https://rslab.gr/Landsat_LST.html]. The distribution of the vulnerable population, people over 65 years and children under 5 years is from the worldpop webpage [https://data.humdata.org/dataset/worldpop-age-and-sex-structures-for-slovakia]. The data about places that are regularly overcrowded are from the Zilina city office. \n",
    "\n",
    "Firstly, we downloaded the Landsat8 Land surface temperature (LST) for the summer months of June, July, and August. We created a raster stack from all LST images and calculated the one layer that represents the highest value for each pixel. We reclassify the raster into 5 classes based on the LST (<20, 20-30, 30-40, 40-50, 50< Celsius). The land surface temperature is not the same as the air temperature. The differences between LST and air temperature  are explained in Fig. 3.\n",
    "\n",
    "Secondly, we downloaded the world population data, for the vulnerable population and classified the raster into 5 equal interval classes.\n",
    "\n",
    "Subsequently, we calculate the Heatwave risk layer by multiplying the LST and population layers, and we get a layer with values from 1 to 25, we also added the Risk matrix for risk assessment interpretation (Fig 2.).\n",
    "\n",
    "Finally, we plotted the overcrowded places, which together with the Heat wave risk map highlighted the most important places (Fig 1.). \n",
    "\n",
    "From the results of the Heat-wave hazard assessment (Look to Heat-wave hazard assessment) was evident that the Heat-wave occurrence should be more frequent in the future. However, we did not use these results directly in the Heat-wave risk map, because the resolution of the climate scenarios is too large for a small city like Zilina. \n",
    "\n",
    "Secondly, we also focus on the influence of the heat on the vegetation. We compute the NDVI characteristics, which provide information on the plant's health. For the calculation of the NDVI, we used the Sentinel2 L2A imagery. We downloaded the Sentinel2 imagery for the summer months, and classified the results based on the NDVI values Fig. 4. The example of the NDVI map is displayed in Fig.5. "
   ]
